# Writing Style (Generated Prose & Docs)

House style for every piece of human-readable text the agent produces: documents, READMEs, the rule files in this repo, reports, research papers, commit and PR bodies, chat prose, and code comments. The goal is clean, plainly-typed, natural writing - not decorative, machine-flavored output.

> This is a readability/house-style rule. It is not a tool for passing AI-generated work off as solely human-authored; follow your institution's or employer's AI-disclosure policy.

---

## The Rule

Write like a person typing on a normal keyboard. Plain ASCII typography. Direct, specific wording. No decorative Unicode and no AI-cliche filler. This applies to the rulebook itself: these `.md` and `.mdc` files MUST follow the same typography they require of everything else. A rule that breaks its own rule is a conflict, and conflicts are banned (see Conflict and Precedence below).

---

## Scope - what this governs

This rule governs **prose**: any human-readable sentence, heading, bullet, table cell, or comment the agent writes. It covers, without exception:

- Product docs, READMEs, `docs/` files, ADRs, changelogs.
- The rule files in this repo (`*.md`) and their Cursor mirrors (`*.mdc`).
- Commit messages, PR titles and bodies, issue and review comments.
- Generated reports, papers, summaries, and chat replies.
- Code comments and docstrings.

It does **not** govern code semantics. See Scope and Exceptions at the end for the precise carve-outs (operators, identifiers, real data, quoted source material).

---

## Typography - NEVER use these characters

Each banned character has a plain ASCII replacement. When in doubt, type what a US keyboard produces.

The left column below is the one place this file deliberately shows the banned characters: they are examples, and Conflict and Precedence rule 2 keeps example characters literal. Never copy them into prose.

| Banned (do not type) | Name | Use instead |
|---|---|---|
| `—` | em dash | a spaced hyphen ` - `, a comma, parentheses, or split the sentence |
| `–` | en dash | a plain hyphen `-` (e.g. `Diffie-Hellman`, `pages 10-12`, `1-5`) |
| `“ ” ‘ ’` | curly / smart quotes | straight quotes `"` and `'` |
| `…` | ellipsis character | three periods `...` |
| `→ ← ⇒` etc. | arrows | `->`, `<-`, `=>` |
| `×` | multiplication sign | the letter `x` (e.g. `2x`, `1920x1080`) |
| `· •` | middle dot / bullet glyph | a Markdown `-` list item, or `*` inline |
| `½ ² ₙ` | fancy fractions / sub / superscripts | `1/2`, `^2`, `_n`, `^T`, `_1` |
| NBSP, thin space, hair space | invisible whitespace | a normal space |

Additional rules:

- **One space after a period.** Never double spaces.
- **No trailing whitespace** at end of lines; end every file with exactly one newline (see `code-formatting.md`).
- **Why this matters:** these glyphs are the clearest fingerprint of machine-pasted text, they break in plain-text terminals, diffs, and grep, and they make `.env`, code, and config copy-paste unreliable. ASCII is portable; fancy typography is not.

When generating files programmatically (building a `.docx`, Markdown, HTML, or any export), run a final pass that rewrites every character above to its ASCII equivalent before saving.

---

## Wording - avoid AI-cliche filler

- **Banned filler words/phrases:** delve, underscore(s) (as a verb), crucial, pivotal, realm, landscape, tapestry, robust (as filler), leverage (as a verb), foster, navigate (figurative), testament, seamless, "it is worth noting", "it is worth stressing", "in essence", "against this backdrop", "plays a vital role", "in today's world", "ever-evolving", "a powerful endorsement".
- **No stacked formulaic transitions** at the start of consecutive paragraphs: Moreover, Furthermore, Additionally, Notably.
- **No empty summarizing flourishes:** "In conclusion, it is clear that...", "Ultimately, this demonstrates...".

---

## DO

- Short, concrete sentences. State the point plainly.
- Vary sentence length and shape; do not make every sentence the same rhythm.
- Pick the specific word over the inflated one: `show` not `underscore`, `key` not `crucial`, `use` not `leverage`, `handle` not `navigate`.
- Cut a sentence that only restates the previous one.

---

## Conflict and Precedence (no opposite rules)

The rulebook must never tell the agent two opposite things. When wording or typography guidance appears in more than one file, resolve it in this order:

1. **`writing-style.md` (this file) is the single authority on typography and prose wording.** No other rule file may contradict it. If another file shows an em dash or banned glyph in its own prose, that is a defect in that file, not a license to use the glyph.
2. **Example payloads win locally.** If a code block, sample log line, regex, or data fixture must contain a specific character to be correct (for example, demonstrating input that itself contains a curly quote), that example keeps the real character. Prose around the example still follows this rule.
3. **External, quoted material is verbatim.** Proper names, standards identifiers, license text, and direct quotations keep their original spelling and punctuation even if it includes banned glyphs.

There is no "prose vs rulebook" exemption. The rulebook is prose and follows this file.

---

## Applying to existing files (migration, not churn)

- **Files you touch:** when you edit any file, convert banned glyphs to ASCII in the sections you change. Do not leave a new em dash behind, and fix obvious ones adjacent to your edit.
- **No unrelated style-only churn:** do not open files you are not working on just to swap dashes. That creates noisy diffs and merge pain.
- **Explicit cleanup is allowed:** a user-requested, repo-wide normalization pass (like converting the whole rulebook to ASCII) is a legitimate task, not "churn." Run it deliberately, in one pass, and re-mirror the `.mdc` copies afterward (see `cursor-sync.md`).

---

## Scope and Exceptions (code and data)

- **Code and math** use whatever characters the syntax requires (operators, identifiers, real symbols). This rule governs prose, not code semantics. A `>=` in code stays `>=`; a multiplication in a math expression stays whatever the notation needs.
- **Real data and fixtures** keep their true bytes. If a test asserts on a string that contains a curly quote, the fixture is correct as written.
- **Proper names, quotes, and standards identifiers** keep their real spelling.
- **ASCII-art structure inside fenced code blocks** (directory trees, flow and sequence diagrams) MAY use box-drawing line characters (`─ │ ├ └ ┌ ┐ ┘ ┤ ┬ ┴`) - they are structure, not prose. This exemption covers line characters only. It does NOT cover arrowheads, checkmarks, or symbol glyphs: still use `->`, `<-`, `yes`/`no`, not `►`, `◄`, `✓`, `○`. In prose (outside code fences), use ASCII for everything.
